This project implements a self-pruning neural network by introducing a custom PrunableLinear layer, 
where each weight is paired with a learnable gate parameter. These gates are passed through a sigmoid function 
to constrain their values between 0 and 1 and are multiplied with the weights, enabling differentiable pruning 
during training. The model is trained on the CIFAR-10 dataset using a standard feed-forward architecture. 
A modified loss function is used, combining cross-entropy loss with a sparsity term defined as the L1 norm 
of all gate values, scaled by a hyperparameter λ. This L1 regularization encourages many gates to move toward zero, 
effectively pruning less important connections. Experiments with different λ values reveal a clear trade-off: 
smaller λ values maintain higher accuracy with less sparsity, while larger λ values increase sparsity at the cost 
of reduced performance. Sparsity is measured as the percentage of gate values below a small threshold, and 
the final distribution of gates shows a strong concentration near zero along with a smaller group of active values, 
confirming that the network successfully learns to prune itself and retain only the most important connections.
